Absolutely! You can reuse much of your existing knowledge and code structure from your blog project. Here’s a step-by-step guide to building a documentation site with nested navigation:

1. **Folder Structure for MDX Files:** Organize your MDX files in a nested folder structure to represent the hierarchy of documentation topics. For example:
   ```
   /docs
   ├── getting-started
   │   ├── introduction.mdx
   │   ├── installation.mdx
   ├── advanced
   │   ├── customization.mdx
   │   ├── deployment.mdx
   ```

2. **Dynamic Routing with Next.js:** Next.js makes it easy to handle dynamic routes based on your folder structure. Use the `getStaticPaths` and `getStaticProps` functions to generate routes and fetch content.

3. **Sidebar Navigation Component:** Create a sidebar navigation component that dynamically reads the structure of the `docs` folder and renders nested menu items.

Here’s how you can implement this:

**a. Parsing the Folder Structure:** Use Node.js to read the file structure during build time. For example:
```js
import fs from 'fs';
import path from 'path';

const docsDirectory = path.join(process.cwd(), 'docs');

export const getDocsStructure = () => {
  const getItems = (dir) => {
    const items = fs.readdirSync(dir);
    return items.map((item) => {
      const itemPath = path.join(dir, item);
      if (fs.statSync(itemPath).isDirectory()) {
        return { name: item, children: getItems(itemPath) };
      } else {
        return { name: item.replace(/\.mdx$/, ''), path: itemPath };
      }
    });
  };
  return getItems(docsDirectory);
};
```

**b. Sidebar Component:** Use the docs structure to render the nested menu.
```jsx
import Link from 'next/link';

const Sidebar = ({ docs }) => {
  const renderItems = (items) => {
    return (
      <ul>
        {items.map((item) => (
          <li key={item.name}>
            {item.children ? (
              <>
                <span>{item.name}</span>
                {renderItems(item.children)}
              </>
            ) : (
              <Link href={`/docs/${item.name}`}>{item.name}</Link>
            )}
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    );
  };

  return <nav>{renderItems(docs)}</nav>;
};

export default Sidebar;
```

