Of course! Ant Design provides a powerful `Table` component that supports sorting and filtering out of the box, which works great for dynamic data. Since you're using TypeScript, you can create an interface for your data type and use it with the `Table`. Here's an example walkthrough:

### Step 1: Define your data structure
First, create a `Product` interface representing the items displayed in your e-commerce dashboard.
```tsx
interface Product {
  key: string;  // unique key for each row
  name: string;
  price: number;
  category: string;
  stock: number;
}
```

### Step 2: Sample Data
Prepare some mock data:
```tsx
const productData: Product[] = [
  { key: '1', name: 'Laptop', price: 1200, category: 'Electronics', stock: 100 },
  { key: '2', name: 'Smartphone', price: 800, category: 'Electronics', stock: 200 },
  { key: '3', name: 'Shoes', price: 100, category: 'Fashion', stock: 50 },
  { key: '4', name: 'Watch', price: 150, category: 'Fashion', stock: 25 },
];
```

### Step 3: Define Columns
Define column configuration for the `Table`.
```tsx
const columns = [
  {
    title: 'Product Name',
    dataIndex: 'name', // Match property name from data
    key: 'name',
    sorter: (a: Product, b: Product) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name),
  },
  {
    title: 'Price',
    dataIndex: 'price',
    key: 'price',
    sorter: (a: Product, b: Product) => a.price - b.price,
    filters: [
      { text: 'Under $500', value: 500 },
      { text: 'Over $500', value: 501 },
    ],
    onFilter: (value: number, record: Product) =>
      value === 500 ? record.price < 500 : record.price >= 500,
  },
  {
    title: 'Category',
    dataIndex: 'category',
    key: 'category',
    filters: [
      { text: 'Electronics', value: 'Electronics' },
      { text: 'Fashion', value: 'Fashion' },
    ],
    onFilter: (value: string, record: Product) => record.category === value,
  },
  {
    title: 'Stock',
    dataIndex: 'stock',
    key: 'stock',
  },
];
```

### Step 4: Rendering the Table
Use the `Table` component from Ant Design to display your data.
```tsx
import React from 'react';
import { Table } from 'antd';

const ProductTable: React.FC = () => {
  return (
    <Table
      columns={columns}
      dataSource={productData}
      pagination={{ pageSize: 5 }} // Optional: controls number of rows per page
    />
  );
};

export default ProductTable;
```

### Step 5: Integrate with Dashboard
You can now integrate this table into your e-commerce dashboard by including the `ProductTable` component wherever needed.

### Advanced Ideas
If you want real-time updates or server-side pagination, you can fetch data from an API endpoint dynamically and update the `dataSource` for the `Table`. For example:
```tsx
const [data, setData] = React.useState<Product[]>([]);
const fetchData = async () => {
  const response = await fetch('/api/products');
  const result = await response.json();
  setData(result);
};
React.useEffect(() => {
  fetchData();
}, []);
```
