To make your table responsive for smaller screens, Ant Design provides a few options. Here's how you can make adjustments to ensure the table columns adapt well:

### Step 1: Use the `Table`'s `scroll` Property
Ant Design allows you to add horizontal scrolling to tables. When the screen width becomes insufficient, the table will enable horizontal scrolling automatically. Set the `scroll` property like this:
```tsx
<Table
  columns={columns}
  dataSource={productData}
  pagination={{ pageSize: 5 }}
  scroll={{ x: 'max-content' }} // Ensures all columns are visible horizontally on small screens
/>
```
This ensures that your table can scroll horizontally if the content exceeds the screen width.

### Step 2: Use `ellipsis` for Long Text
If you have columns with long text that might overflow, use the `ellipsis` property to truncate the text and display it with a tooltip.
```tsx
const columns = [
  {
    title: 'Product Name',
    dataIndex: 'name',
    key: 'name',
    ellipsis: true, // Truncates text and adds a tooltip automatically
    sorter: (a: Product, b: Product) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name),
  },
  // other columns...
];
```
This will ensure that excessively long names or descriptions don’t break the layout on smaller screens.

### Step 3: Use `responsive` Property
You can configure columns to appear or hide based on screen size using the `responsive` property. For example:
```tsx
const columns = [
  {
    title: 'Product Name',
    dataIndex: 'name',
    key: 'name',
    responsive: ['xs', 'sm', 'md', 'lg'], // Available on all screen sizes
  },
  {
    title: 'Price',
    dataIndex: 'price',
    key: 'price',
    responsive: ['sm', 'md', 'lg'], // Hidden on extra small screens
  },
  {
    title: 'Category',
    dataIndex: 'category',
    key: 'category',
    responsive: ['md', 'lg'], // Hidden on small and extra small screens
  },
  {
    title: 'Stock',
    dataIndex: 'stock',
    key: 'stock',
    responsive: ['lg'], // Only visible on large screens
  },
];
```
By setting `responsive`, you control which columns are displayed on various screen sizes.

### Step 4: Combine with Ant Design Grid System
Ant Design provides a responsive grid system (`Row` and `Col`) that you can use to wrap your table. For small screens, you could reduce padding or add a scrollable container.
```tsx
import { Row, Col } from 'antd';

const ResponsiveTable: React.FC = () => {
  return (
    <Row>
      <Col xs={24} sm={24} md={24} lg={18} xl={16}>
        <Table
          columns={columns}
          dataSource={productData}
          pagination={{ pageSize: 5 }}
          scroll={{ x: 'max-content' }}
        />
      </Col>
    </Row>
  );
};
```
### Step 5: Style Adjustments
Finally, you can use CSS alongside Ant Design's customization framework to tweak table styling further. For example:
```css
.ant-table {
  font-size: 14px; /* Adjust font size for better readability on small screens */
}
.ant-table-thead > tr > th {
  padding: 8px; /* Reduce padding to save space */
}
.ant-table-cell {
  white-space: nowrap; /* Prevent text from wrapping */
}
```
These steps should ensure your table works beautifully on both large and small screens. Do you need help implementing any of these?

