Great! For the reverse proxy setup, you'll need to create or edit your Nginx server block file. Here's an example configuration:

```nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    listen [::]:80;
    server_name yourdomain.com;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:5000; # Replace with your backend server's address
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}

server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    listen [::]:443 ssl;
    server_name yourdomain.com;

    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/privkey.pem;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:5000; # Replace with your backend server's address
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}
```

Here’s a breakdown:
1. The first server block listens on port 80 and is used for HTTP traffic. You can redirect this to HTTPS using Certbot, which will add the necessary rules automatically.
2. The second server block listens on port 443 for HTTPS traffic and uses the SSL certificate you obtained.
3. The `proxy_pass` directive forwards incoming requests to your backend server (e.g., a web application running on port 5000).

After saving the configuration, test it:
```bash
sudo nginx -t
```
If there are no errors, restart Nginx:
```bash
sudo systemctl reload nginx
```
